Dataset Joyce_2019_Cm

This dataset is from Joyce et al.Â (2019): https://doi.org/10.1016/j.marenvres.2019.02.010

  • Contains n=67 feeding trials.
  • Raw data is available.
  • Single-prey experiments ran for 8 hours, multi-prey for 2 hours.
  • Eaten prey were not replaced during single-prey experiments, but replaced in multi-prey.
  • We fitted a mix of ODE-based predictions and direct FR predictions, accordingly.
  • Holling-2 was identified as the best fitting model. Holling-3 and the New FR performed equally.
  • The model predicts a preference for prey 1, no switching.
  • Multi-prey data was systematically under-predicted. This is likely because of strong diffences in experimental duration.

Single-species experiments were performed without prey replacement for 8 hours, while multi-species experiments were performed with prey replacement for 2 hours.

df.single.1$Time = 8/24 # [days]

df.single.1$Replaced = 0
df.single.2$Replaced = 0
df.multi$Replaced = 1

                    Prey1.Eaten = c(df.single.1$Prey1.Eaten, df.single.2$Prey1.Eaten, df.multi$Prey1),

                    Time = c(df.single.1$Time, df.single.2$Time, df.multi$Time),
                    Replaced = c(df.single.1$Replaced, df.single.2$Replaced, df.multi$Replaced)
)

Data has to be coded as a named list for Stan. Single- and multi-species experiments are different in their values for Time and Replaced (see above).

data.stan = list(n = nrow(df.all),
                 m = 2,
                 N_0 = as.matrix(df.all[, 1:2]),
                 N_e = as.matrix(df.all[, 3:4]),
                 Time = df.all$Time,
                 Replaced = df.all$Replaced
)

Model fitting

For all models, posterior distributions are sampled using 3 chains, 1000 warmup steps and 2000 sampling steps, each. Initial values init are provided for all parameters. Convergence of MCMC is verified through Rhat value close to 1 and sufficient number of effective samples n_eff.

chains = 3

Fit Holling 2

init = rep(list(list(a = c(1,1),
                     h = c(1/100,1/100))
),chains)

fit1 = sampling(
  model.H2,
  data = data.stan,
  chains = chains,
  warmup = 1000,
  iter = 3000,
  cores = 3,
  init = init,
  refresh = 100
)
print(fit1, pars=c("a","h"))

Model comparison

Extract log-likelihood values for all fits and compute predictive performance with leave-one-out cross validation using the loo package.

lik1 = extract_log_lik(fit1, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff1 = relative_eff(exp(lik1), cores=4) 
loo1 = loo(lik1, r_eff=reff1, cores=4)

lik2 = extract_log_lik(fit2, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff2 = relative_eff(exp(lik2), cores=4) 
loo2 = loo(lik2, r_eff=reff2, cores=4)

lik3 = extract_log_lik(fit3, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff3 = relative_eff(exp(lik3), cores=4) 
loo3 = loo(lik3, r_eff=reff3, cores=4)

lik4 = extract_log_lik(fit4, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff4 = relative_eff(exp(lik4), cores=4) 
loo4 = loo(lik4, r_eff=reff4, cores=4)

loo_compare(loo1, loo2, loo3, loo4)
       elpd_diff se_diff
model2    0.0       0.0 
model4  -13.1       9.5 
model1  -33.6      31.3 
model3 -121.9      28.2

Holling 3 has the highest elpd score, but including uncertainty (se_diff) it is equivalent to Holling-2. Due to parsimony, Holling-2 is identified as the best fitting model.

Its posterior distributions of all parameters and their multivariate correlation are plotted.

plot(As.mcmc.list(fit1)[, 1:4])

correlationPlot(as.matrix(fit1)[, 1:4])

Posterior predictions for best fitting model

The correct MSFR model function is selected, which has the output (negative) functional response. 1000 samples from the posterior distribution are chosen randomly. For single-species experiments, predictions are generated through numerical simulation of ODEs with a duration of 8/24 day. In multi-species experiments prey were replaced, predictions are computed directly as feeding rate multiplied by experimental duration (2/24 day). Their median and 90% credible intervals are plotted against observed data.

MSFR = Holling2

n.post = 1000
n.pred = 20
post = as.matrix(fit1)[, 1:4]
set.seed(100)
post = post[sample(1:nrow(post),n.post), ]

Single-species prey 1

N10.pred = seq(0.1, 64, length.out=n.pred)
N1E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:n.pred){
    out = ode(y = c(N=c(N10.pred[i], 0.0)), times = c(0,8/24), func = MSFR, parms = params) 
    N1E.pred[k,i] = N10.pred[i]-out[2,2]
  }
}

N1E.pred.qs = apply(N1E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(df.single.1$Prey1, jitter(df.single.1$Prey1.Eaten, factor=0.3), 
     xlim=c(0,64), ylim=c(0,64),
     xlab="Prey 1 offered", ylab="Prey 1 eaten",
     main="Single-species feeding: Prey 1")
polygon( c(N10.pred, rev(N10.pred)), 
         c(N1E.pred.qs[1, ], rev(N1E.pred.qs[3, ])), 
         border=NA,
         col=adjustcolor("blue", alpha.f=0.2)
)
lines(N10.pred, N1E.pred.qs[2, ], col="blue", lwd=2)

Single-species prey 2

N20.pred = seq(0.1, 64, length.out=n.pred)
N2E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:n.pred){

    N2E.pred[k,i] = N20.pred[i]-out[2,3]
  }
}

N2E.pred.qs = apply(N2E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(df.single.2$Prey2, jitter(df.single.2$Prey2.Eaten, factor=0.3),

Multi-species relative consumption

Multi-species predictions are computed along a gradient of relative composition of N1 and N2 with N1+N2=20.

N0.total = 20

N10.pred = seq(0, N0.total, length.out=n.pred)
N20.pred = N0.total-N10.pred
N1E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)
N2E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:n.pred){
    out = -(2/24)*unlist(MSFR(t=0, N=c(N10.pred[i], N20.pred[i]), parms=params)) 
    N1E.pred[k,i] = out[1]
    N2E.pred[k,i] = out[2]
  }
}

N1E.pred.qs = apply(N1E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))
N2E.pred.qs = apply(N2E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

# make relative 
N1E.pred.rel = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)
N2E.pred.rel = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)
for(k in 1:n.post){
  N1E.pred.rel[k, ] = N1E.pred[k, ]/(N1E.pred[k, ]+N2E.pred[k, ])
  N2E.pred.rel[k, ] = N2E.pred[k, ]/(N1E.pred[k, ]+N2E.pred[k, ])
}

N1E.pred.rel.qs = apply(N1E.pred.rel, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))
N2E.pred.rel.qs = apply(N2E.pred.rel, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(df.multi$Prey1/(df.multi$Prey1+df.multi$Prey2),
     jitter(df.multi$Prey1.Eaten/(df.multi$Prey1.Eaten+df.multi$Prey2.Eaten),factor=1),
     xlim=c(0,1), ylim=c(0,1),
     xlab="Proportion prey 1 offered", ylab="Proportion prey 1 eaten",
     main="Multi-species preference")
abline(0,1)
polygon( c(N10.pred/N0.total, rev(N10.pred/N0.total)), 
         c(N1E.pred.rel.qs[1, ], rev(N1E.pred.rel.qs[3, ])), 
         border=NA,
         col=adjustcolor("blue", alpha.f=0.2)
)
lines(N10.pred/N0.total, N1E.pred.rel.qs[2, ], col="blue", lwd=2)

The model predicts a preference for prey 1.

Multi-species feeding

Since multi-species experiments were performed with a fixed number of total prey only (N1+N2=20), predicted feeding rates on both species can be plotted along this gradient against the data.

plot(NA, xlim=c(0,20), ylim=c(0,20), xaxt="n", ylab="", xlab="",

         border=NA,
         col=adjustcolor("blue", alpha.f=0.2)
)
polygon( c(20-N20.pred, rev(20-N20.pred)), 
         c(N2E.pred.qs[1, ], rev(N2E.pred.qs[3, ])), 
         border=NA,

Multi-species observed vs.Â predicted

Additionally, median predicted numbers of eaten prey (N1E and N2E) are computed and plotted against observed data points.

N1E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=nrow(df.multi))
N2E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=nrow(df.multi))

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:nrow(df.multi)){
    out = -(2/24)*unlist(MSFR(t=0, N=c(df.multi$Prey1[i],df.multi$Prey2[i]), parms=params)) 
    N1E.pred[k,i] = out[1]
    N2E.pred[k,i] = out[2]
  }
}

N1E.pred.qs = apply(N1E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))
N2E.pred.qs = apply(N2E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(NULL, xlim=c(0,20), ylim=c(0,20), xlab="Predicted", ylab="Observed",
